Critical elements of SPEG's prevention program include:
¿	Developing and maintaining safety information on all processes and associated equipment and systems;
¿	Performing comprehensive risk assessment studies of all critical processes and equipment to control and mitigate identified hazards;
¿	Formal written operating and preventive maintenance procedures and schedules to ensure the safe and efficient operation and maintenance of critical processes and equipment;
¿	A comprehensive training and certification program to ensure that all site personnel, process operators, contractors and supplier personnel are adequately trained and certified to perform process-related activities in a safe and efficient manner;
¿	An aggressive site security program, coordinated with local, state and federal law enforcement agencies to ensure the security and safety of the facility and its' operations; and
¿	A multi-tiered audit and investigation program to evaluate the terminal's accidental release prevention program's effectiveness in preventing and/or mitigating the offsite consequences of an accidental release of the regulated substance.

FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

Since construction and startup operations there has not been an accidental release of propane, or any other hazardous substance at the Suburban Propane Elk Grove Terminal that has resulted in any deaths or offsite injuries; property or environmental damage; evacuations or sheltering in place.  The last unplanned and/or non-routine release of Propane was on  September 13, 2005.  A non-employ

ee driver failed to check or relieve pressure prior to disconnecting a  live hose.  The non-reportable release event  was mitigated by site personnel.  No action was required by offsite emergency response agencies.

EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM

The Suburban Elk Grove Terminal has developed and maintains a comprehensive Emergency Action Plan (EAP) which details specific procedures to be implemented by site personnel in the event of an emergency, including:
Process and equipment shut down procedures;
¿	Fire protection procedures;
¿	Evacuation procedures;
¿	Emergency Responder notification procedures;
¿	Public notification procedures;
¿	Post-emergency investigation and reporting requirements; and
¿	Post-emergency process systems inspection and startup procedures

The Terminal's EAP has been coordinated with, and is regularly inspected by, local offsite responders, including the Elk Grove Fire Department, the Elk Grove Police Department, the Sacramento County Sheriff's Department and the Sacramento Metropolitan Fire District. The Elk Grove Terminal maintains onsite fire-fighting and emergency response systems and equipment to support and augment offsite emergency response resources as well.  The site's emergency response systems and equipment are maintained in accordance with the site's accidental release prevention program requirements.

PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY

In response to recommendations from the 2009 Process Hazard Assessment (PHAs) revalidation, SPEG has completed the following process safety upgrades:
¿	In 2010 SPEG installed an additional refrigeration system upstream of, and in-line with,  the existing system to mitigate and control over-pressurization of the bulk storage tanks during filling (loading) operations under specified conditions; and
¿	Upgraded and expanded the Terminal's existing security systems to accommodate the Terminal's new site access route.

